<h2>Color Has Memory</h2>
<p>Colors don't have universal meanings — but they have cultural and contextual associations that are powerful within any given market. Green speaks to growth, nature, and trust in Western contexts. Gold speaks to premium, achievement, and scarcity. Deep navy speaks to authority, expertise, and reliability. These aren't rules. They're inherited associations that your brand either aligns with or deliberately subverts.</p>
<p>The strategic question isn't "what does this color mean?" It's: "what does this color mean to the specific people we're trying to reach, in the context of the industry we're in?" A green that signals freshness and health in the food industry might signal inexperience in the finance industry. Context is everything.</p>

